[1] Thailand (Bangkok)
Date: Thu 12 May 2005
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Reuters AlertNet, London, UK, 12 May 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/BKK93822.htm>

Severe dengue outbreak kills 12 in Thailand
-------------------------------------------
Thailand, where mosquitoes are a pest in every home, is facing a severe
outbreak of dengue fever, with 12 people dead so far this year [2005],
almost double the toll a year earlier, a health official said on Thursday
[12 May 2005].
Dengue has infected 7200 people as of 7 May 2005, of whom 12 have died, up
from 7 deaths in the same period last year, Department of Disease Control
chief Thawat Suntrajarn told Reuters.
"No province in Thailand is immune from dengue outbreaks, because we have
mosquitoes everywhere," Thawat said, adding the outbreak usually peaks
between late June and July when wet season rains are the heaviest.
The tropical disease made headlines this week [2nd week May 2005] when
thousands of people queued at hospitals in Bangkok to donate blood for a 13
year old sufferer. The boy died on Wednesday [11 May 2005] after suffering
internal bleeding for nearly a week.
The disease -- which killed 176 of 114 800 infected people in 2002 -- is
characterized by high fever, rash, headaches, and severe muscle and joint pain.
******
[2] Thailand (Bangkok)
Date: Thu 12 May 2005
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: MCOT: TNA English News, Bangkok, Thailand, 12 May 2005 [edited]
<http://www.mcot.org/query.php?nid=38407>

Thai doctors investigate death of young dengue fever victim
-----------------------------------------------------------
Doctors are carrying out a forensic investigation into the death of a
teenage boy who died of dengue fever in a Bangkok hospital this week [2nd
week May 2005]. His parents donated his body for research into the
mosquitoborne disease in the hope that the study will help lead to the
development of a vaccine to save millions of children.
The 13 year old sufferer was pronounced dead at Bangkok's Ramathibordhi
Hospital on Wednesday [11 May 2005] night after days of treatment. His
parents decided to donate his body to Mahidol University's Vaccine
Development Center for the study. "The center will analyze which strain of
the dengue virus killed the boy. We'll also be looking to see if it's a new
strain, even though we know mutations are extremely rare," center director
Dr Suthee Yoksan said. "We can't ignore any possibility, because dengue
fever is endemic in both Thailand and Indonesia," he said.
Dr Suthee said the study could take a year or more. He described it as the
world's most in-depth study on dengue fever in 25 years and as inspired
medical research. "We thank the boy's parents for allowing the doctors to
carry out a forensic study on his body. We'll be looking at the mechanism
of the virus once it infects a victim and to see which organs are major
targets," he said.
Dr Suthee said he hoped the study would eventually lead to the development
of an effective vaccine against the disease and help save the lives of
millions of children. He said the center would coordinate with other
international organizations that are trying to develop a vaccine and would
apply for research funding from the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation.
Earlier this week [2nd week May 2005], the Public Health Ministry reported
some 6000 Thais had been infected with dengue fever so far this year
[2005], most of them young children.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is a very touching story in that the parents of the young dengue
hemorrhagic fever victim generously donated their child's body for
research, hoping to find the etiology of the disease and to produce an
effective vaccine. The season for dengue fever has just started. Among 7200
cases as of 7 May 2005, 12 deaths have been reported in Thailand. The
outbreaks usually peak between late June and July, when wet season rains
are heaviest. - Mod.RY]
