[3] Thailand (Bangkok)
Date: Sat 14 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: MCOT: TNA English News, Bangkok, Thailand, 14 May 2005 [edited]
<http://www.mcot.org/query.php?nid=38470>

Ministry sets up 24 hour dengue fever hotline
---------------------------------------------
The Department of Disease Control has set up a 24-hour telephone helpline
in the fight against the latest outbreak of dengue fever.
With dengue fever having claimed the lives of 14 people this year [2005],
with another 7000 ill with the mosquitoborne disease, the department has
established a helpline with information on symptoms of the illness and how
to control it.
The issue of dengue fever is close to the heart of prime minister Thaksin
Shinawatra, who today [Sat 14 May 2005] revealed that his younger brother
had died of the disease, aged 25. Although the disease is rarely fatal in
adults, the prime minister said that a misdiagnosis of his brother's
condition had contributed to his untimely death. In its early stages,
dengue fever is easy to confuse with ordinary influenza, but within a few
days, a patient may be experiencing internal hemorrhaging.
******
[4] Thailand (Nakhon Si Thammarat)
Date: Sat 14 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: MCOT: TNA English News, Nakhon Sri Thammarat, Thailand, 11 May 2005
[edited]

Concern over dengue fever outbreak in Nakhon Sri Thammarat
----------------------------------------------------------
The chief medical officer of the southern province of Nakhon Si Thammarat
today [Sat 14 May 2005] expressed concern over latest outbreak of dengue
fever there, which has already claimed the life of one patient and left
another 378 receiving treatment.
Dr Nopporn Chuenklin, who called for officials to help control the
mosquitoborne disease, said that most of the cases were in children aged
6-13 years.
The disease is said to be particularly prevalent in Thung Song and Na Bon
districts, where officials are working to spray insecticide around schools
and houses.
******
[5] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Sat 14 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Townsville Bulletin, Queensland, Australia, Sat 14 May 2005 [edited]
<http://townsvillebulletin.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,7034,15282634%255E14787,00.html>

City suburb hit by dengue outbreak
----------------------------------
A dengue fever outbreak has struck Townsville. The potentially fatal virus,
carried by "the cockroach of all mosquitoes", has no vaccine and no cure.
After a Currajong man in his 40s was found ill with dengue yesterday [Fri
13 May 2005], all homes within 200 meters of his home were inspected by
authorities and homeowners alerted to the dangers.
Dengue does not naturally occur in North Queensland, but the dengue
mosquito is common, and outbreaks can occur when the virus is transmitted
to the local mosquito population by infected international travelers or
residents.
Health authorities yesterday [Fri 13 May 2005] said the man had been bitten
in Townsville. They warned residents to take precautions.
Queensland Health Tropical Public Health Unit Environmental Health Service
Acting director Damien Farrington urged residents to take immediate action
to eradicate dengue. "There is no medical cure for dengue fever and no
vaccine," he said. "The serious form of the disease, dengue hemorrhagic
fever, can be fatal, especially in young children."
There were 58 cases in Townsville in the 2003-04 outbreak. Experts are
working together to conduct house to house inspections and mosquito
eradication. "It's the cockroach of the mosquitoes, because it really only
lives around peoples' homes," Mr Farrington said. "In this case, we are
still waiting on more tests to find out what type it is."
There are 4 types of dengue viruses: 1, 2, 3 and 4. Anyone infected with
one type of dengue will only be immune to that type and will be at risk of
developing severe symptoms if they contract another type.
A far northern woman died from dengue last year [2004]. In 1992-93, there
was an epidemic in Townsville with 900 people infected. Infected residents
may have no symptoms or experience a mild fever.
Dengue hemorrhagic fever or dengue shock syndrome can be fatal. All
patients with dengue hemorrhagic fever need to be taken to the hospital for
fluid therapy and monitoring. Townsville City Council staff are working
closely with mosquito control experts to conduct house inspections and
mosquito eradications.
[byline: Vicki Campion]
